<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/7036573-pamela-j"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1371734656i/7036573._UX100_CR0,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/7036573-pamela-j">Pamela J</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">Dave, That&apos;s a string of four questions. I&apos;ll answer the first three. We don&apos;t really get the answers, which frustrates readers like my students. But <a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">Dave, That's a string of four questions. I'll answer the first three. We don't really get the answers, which frustrates readers like my students. But once I explain that the novel stages how the sherrif and townspeople <i>already</i> make up their minds about what they think they know. The novel is an exploration of what we think we know vs what we actually know. Once you entertain that idea, the novel becomes much more interesting and maybe helps you answer your question about Hightower's place in the novel.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
