<div id="review_2821098488" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2821098488" />
    <a title="Sharon Metcalf" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/49089020-sharon-metcalf"><img alt="Sharon Metcalf" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1451815807p2/49089020.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2821098488?book_show_action=true">Apr 11, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sharon Metcalf" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sharon Metcalf" href="/user/show/49089020-sharon-metcalf">Sharon Metcalf</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/49089020-sharon-metcalf?shelf=2020">2020</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/49089020-sharon-metcalf?shelf=owned">owned</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2821098488" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7105958383085213875">It was May 2019 and a few of my GoodReads friends had just read <b>Light In August</b> by William Faulkner. Each of them rated the book well providing glowing words about the writing but equally they commented on the difficulty of the book. Not having read any Faulkner myself but being aware of his Nobel prize for Literature I was intrigued, slightly intimidated, but decided I was up for the challenge. <br/><br/>As it turns out I didn&apos;t read the book but listened to it and I think there were definite pro&apos;s and c</span>
  <span id="freeText7105958383085213875" style="display:none">It was May 2019 and a few of my GoodReads friends had just read <b>Light In August</b> by William Faulkner. Each of them rated the book well providing glowing words about the writing but equally they commented on the difficulty of the book. Not having read any Faulkner myself but being aware of his Nobel prize for Literature I was intrigued, slightly intimidated, but decided I was up for the challenge. <br /><br />As it turns out I didn't read the book but listened to it and I think there were definite pro's and con's to this eventuality. On the downside, with writing of this caliber I often feel the need to see the words in their written form, to go back, re-read and simply savior passages. That was definitely the case for this novel so though I've now finished the audio book I've just purchased a copy of the eBook and will go back to feast my eyes. On the upside, Faulkner displayed an incredible skill for bringing the Southern dialect to the page and it was a treat for the ears listening to Will Patton narrating and bringing the characters to life - even if I frequently disliked said characters. <br /><br />Thinking back on the novel I realise the action and events only spanned a six week period yet through the inner dialogue and stream-of-consciousness of the characters, readers were taken back multiple generations. These personal histories helped provide context for the character's thought processes and explained behaviours. But, at the same time this way of delivering the story could easily confuse (perhaps explaining some of the difficulty attributed to it). This was a book that required patience. Faulkner changed perspective often and I didn't always know how a particular section fit into the whole story. That said, at no stage did I ever doubt the author would bring it all together. My trust was well placed and indeed the major puzzle pieces fell into place - although there were still a number of unresolved plot lines by books end. <br /><br />Though I felt it ended on at least one note of hope, Light In August was not at all light in content. In fact it was dark, at times violent and many of the characters were not remotely like able. If Faulkner's representation of the 1930's South is remotely factual it gives readers plenty to mull over. Attitudes to race, sex, class and religion in the American South were major themes touched upon through the inner struggles of his characters and he does not paint a pretty picture. <br /><br />Having accepted the challenge of reading a Faulkner I'm certainly not sorry. I'm confident this reading experience stretched my mind. It also had me Googling to learn more about the author, his writing style, and his books (not just this one). Though my review is not a thorough analysis of the book and doesn't even hint at the plot (plenty of others will do this for you) I enjoyed the experience and definitely feel inclined to try another.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7105958383085213875" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


